speaker announcement!! we are so very proud to have executive chef nora haron join us on november 3rd. come and hear about nora's story of survival, success, and leadership as an aapi womxn. together we'll explore issues impacting our communities and celebrate powerful aapi leaders who are changing the game.
.
nora haron is breaking through glass ceilings and redefining the culinary industry with her south east asian dishes and and unique flavorful fusions. nora is an executive chef and partner at 4p's hospitality group, and women's advocate. born and raised in singapore, nora received hands on culinary training through helping her mother‚Äôs catering business. but her love for food began while working in lucca, italy working as a shoe designer. after learning how to cook from local italian women she returned to the us and enrolled in san francisco‚Äôs baking institute. since then her passion for food, drive and pursuit to break gender and racial barriers has led her to great places. nora has worked as the executive chef at drip line oakland, monkey forest road and was the head kitchen manager/culinary operations manager for blue bottle coffee. she's also been featured on pbs and food network.
.
she is currently the culinary consultant for medd cafes located in saudi arabia and has co-authored two cook books with boba guys and east bay cooks. she is currently on the advisory board for aapi women lead. follow her at @noraharon_oak
.

text:
india is a country with more female deities then male. in the wake of #metoo campaigns in india exposing sexual assaults and advances, the latest revelation being that of singer sona mohapatra against kailash kher, let this nine-day festival which celebrates the triumph of good over evil wake us up from the slumber of ignorance. this is what the festival in the present era could signify. it‚Äôs not mentally safe to keep your mouths locked out from such incidences, if not take action at least vent. sexual assaults can make people hate/lose respect towards their body, and as a result make them consider their personal worth and self-esteem to merely their physical body & physical relationships, distort their understanding of relationships, keep anger and frustration and lead to depression. it‚Äôs a serious issue. speak up. it‚Äôs not your mistake. you could not have stopped it because the body goes into shock. 
this can happen with males too. expressing this frustration in a sane environment can make you vent your hidden anger.
#women #metoo #mentalhealth #notyourmistake #navratri

text:
#navratri2018 day 1: mahakali

what does a closed fist mean to you?

mystery and secrets, because you can't see what's being held?

violence; the threat of a punch?

power and solidarity, because fists are held up during so many of the protests around the world today?

suffocation, holding it all in: clenching your fist so the rage and grief and pain doesn't come spilling out?

like mahakali, what each one of us sees can be different. to some, she is a benevolent mother; to others, she is a fearsome avenger. some see her as beauty itself, and others, as so repulsive that they do not even dare worship her.

it all depends on circumstance.

it  seems like an awful time for women around the world; the more the stories of #metoo come out into the open, the more women seem to be mocked at, the more the violence seems to increase. my heart hurts from the constant, never-ending misogyny, the sexism everywhere i look. and in these times, i remember that we are, like mahakali, a clenched fist. waiting, watching, to become whatever we need to be.

stay strong, my sisters. üëä‚úä #navratri2018 #navratri #indianfestivals #indianmythology #hindu #hinduism #kali #mahakali #womenempowerment #feminist #feminism #feministandproud #instart #art #artistsoninstagram #artstagram #arttherapy

text:
over the past few days, the third wave of the #metoo movement in india has gained unprecedented momentum in the country. women have come forward with stories of sexual harassment and assault at the hands of prominent ‚Äòprogressive‚Äô men in india including well-known stand-up comics and senior journalists and authors. the movement began late last year with raya sarkar's¬†losha, (list of sexual harassers in academia). while this is a hopeful moment for feminism in india, it can also be quite overwhelming for those affected by sexual harassment.

the onslaught of narratives of sexual harassment being shared on social media can cause retraumatisation or a re-experiencing of trauma for survivors. it can also be triggering if your perpetrator has been called out by another person, you knew the perpetrator in other capacities or if somebody you know has come out as a survivor of sexual assault. non-survivors may also experience vicarious trauma, due to continuous exposure to traumatic narratives. to have a healthier engagement with the movement, it is important for us to prioritise self-care and take care of ourselves emotionally.

article by ahla matra of altstory

on this world mental health day, let's remember to prioritise our self care too. read the full article in the link in bio.

text:
i think there are a lot of women out there who could use this right now. i made this tonight. just a quick sketch. 
there is a photo series of the awful things said about women painted on their bodies, and it is poignant. the things that happen to us get etched into us. but maybe if we practice positive self-talk, we are open with one another, and we lift each other up, we can get through the abuse and come out stronger. 
maybe we can re-write what is written on us.  thanks again for the inspiration photo #angelbunnythug @itsthugsbunny.  #metoo #survivor #sexualassault #sexualassaultsurvivor #womensupportingwomen #speakup #findyourstrength #morethanmybody #quotes #positivevibes #vulnerability

text:
the #metoo movement that started with #tanushreedutta has given space to voices in multiple sectors. 
this is also a time when the trope of a woman being a woman's enemy is crumbling. this trope has been used by patriarchy to divide women and keep them separate. give them work that takes up all their time. they think: if women don't talk to each other how will they support each other?

the #metoo and #timesup movements in #india have broken this thinking. women are confiding in each other, trusting each other, and forming a united front. i see so many women come out in support for another woman when some entitled a$$hole says 'why now? why not earlier?' or 'do you want to come on big boss next?' historically women communities have been a safe space for women and children. it's a space where one is not judged, and where one feels at home. safe spaces are created. they don't just automatically exist. let's maintain these spaces for each other. remember someday you might need them too.

text:
"you smear somebody with falsehoods and all the rest," pelosi detailed, "and then you merchandise it. and then you (gesturing to the media) write it, and then they say, 'see, it's reported in the press that this, this, this, and this.' so they have that validation that the press reported the smear, and then it's called the 'wrap-up smear.'" "and now i‚Äôm going to merchandise the press's report on the smear that we made," she repeated. "it's a tactic. and it's self-evident." of course, this is the exact template used in the kavanaugh smear. uncorroborated, salacious, off-the-wall allegations of sexual misconduct, including accusations of high school gang rape rings, were leaked to the media by the left to smear kavanaugh. with the "validation" of a complicit, biased media's reporting, democrats endlessly pushed the baseless accusations, further ruining the reputation of mr. kavanaugh and republicans in general. senator dianne feinstein was even able speak of gang rape rings during a highly-publicized senate judiciary committee hearing because of the tactic so eloquently explained by pelosi.

it didn't matter that all of the allegations were uncorroborated with serious credibility gaps; the damage was already done to a good man, all for political gain. the "wrap-up smear," if you will, was completed, and kavanaugh had his name forever tarred.

text:
‚Äúno shame , no guilt , speak up ‚Äú
.
as a mother of three children , and caring for all children , and supporter of metoo movement.  i will share with you my vision for now and the future .  because it‚Äôs not enough to encourage to speak up . more important is to have a plan to deal with the wounds now , and to know how to do it . to have a plan for the future to prevent it from occurring again . .
what is your plan for now : open the wound , disinfect it . let the world know the truth . unite in this truth with strength and power ; no shame and no guilt .  it‚Äôs not your fault , it‚Äôs not a mistake , it‚Äôs wrong doing done to you . and now ...
.
now : hold them accountable for their actions . make an end to this . elect one of you to represent you . let the justice system , and the people listen. demand justice for you and for all who were abused . .
healing : address trauma such as ptsd , anxiety and depression . .

text: today i rode the train to work, as i do most days. but today i witnessed a telling and tragic human interaction. it made me furious ‚Äî and sad. a beautiful, black pregnant woman boarded a packed train during rush hour on her way to work. the middle-aged, white man sitting in the handicap seat, with no visible disability, appeared astonished and annoyed when she asked to sit down. the woman and i made eye contact after this incident ‚Äî with no words spoken a million were shared. we got off the train and released our disgust, both also disappointed in ourselves for not making a stink. it‚Äôs exhausting to fight the good fight. thank you #christineblaseyford for your courage. i am overwhelmed with emotion recently, but mostly filled with gratitude and inspired by your leadership. you‚Äôve united women. please, everyone, try a little harder to be better people. at the very least don‚Äôt be assholes. we‚Äôre all responsible for the community we create. apathy is ignorance.  #ibelieveher #metoo thank you @pablodelcan for this piece of art.

we must find paths to justice outside of prisons, police, the courts, ice and the state. we must be unrelenting in our quest to understand and experience what ‚Äújustice‚Äù is‚Äîwhat it could be. how can we effectively fight for justice when most of us do not even know what it truly means?
.
we must understand that justice is bound up with accountability and healing. questions about justice are inevitably questions about accountability; and questions about accountability are inevitably questions about justice. we must start by practicing accountability with each other and ourselves. and we must interrogate why this is so hard for us.
.
we need to spend time with the questions: what would justice have looked like for the times you‚Äôve been wronged or harmed? and what would justice have looked like for the times you‚Äôve harmed or wronged someone else? üåø
.
.

.
.

.

text:
‚Äúvirginity is a purely patriarchal concept based on biological illiteracy and a desire to control and own women‚Äôs sexuality. it is not noble. so while i want to take the ‚Äòreasonable‚Äô approach that frames virginity as a woman‚Äôs sexual choice i cannot and will not. because a desire to refrain from sexual contact for a myriad of reasons is separate from the value assessment that virginity assigns women.‚Äù ‚Äì ghana feminism creator obaa boni on twitter at @obaa_boni
.
how i healed from my ‚Äúvirginity‚Äù being weaponized by my rapist (discussed in previous post)? i rejected virginity. i threw it in the garbage with the rest of the cisheteropatriarchal garbage. obaa boni helped me see this was valid, helped entrench me in how empowering it is to stop seeking any value from a system meant to inherently dehumanize us.
.
i also learned even more about how truly ‚Äúbiologically illiterate‚Äù the concept is.  like this:
.
‚Äúthat the hymen isn't a membrane that needs to bleed or be broken during intercourse‚Äîit's actually just small, usually elastic folds of mucous tissue that only partially cover the vaginal opening and can, but don‚Äôt always, tear if stretched.‚Äù
.
i cried in relief when i learned you do not have to bleed the first time you have penetrative sex. in fact, if you are bleeding it likely was not good sex or worse it was rape.  i cried because will had shown me the blood as if in triumph when he was actually proving he raped me.
.
here‚Äôs another fun fact your hymen heals. your hymen can grow back. your hymen could very well be with you, stretching, sliding, and just hanging out as a protective little membrane doing nothing that is of consequence to your purity or your status as someone who has or has not had vaginal penetrative sex.
. 
in fact, traditional virginity concepts, like all patriarchal concepts, draw lines around cis, binary bodies and heterosexual penile-vagina penetrative sex. it‚Äôs an inherently transphobic, homophobic concept. all patriarchal concepts are because they try to establish a world where cis women are subject to cis men through heterosexual marriage and patriarchy ‚Äì any aberrations are punished.
.

text:
‚òΩ yoni~ a sanskrit word that means a ‚Äúcrack between the worlds, or a portal for life to come through‚Äù and also a pretty word that means vagina, which resonated with me and allowed me to release the hush hush things that relate to womanhood and sexuality. big change is happening in the world...

text:
yesterday i was having a discussion with one of my contemporaries about #metoo. we went over some of the really sad cases reiterating how the devils definitely need to be put to task. it's awesome that a woman finally is outing the person who insulted her, gave her a harrowing time and didn't take it well when she said a "no". but then, there are also cases that do not belong in this raging storm. a man who realised his indiscretion immediately and apologised profusely. why put him to task when he never repeated his mistake. that too after 13 years. and the woman in question viciously dragged the wife of the man into the picture now. he has a 13-year-old daughter, too. couldn't the woman just wipe that tiny incident from her mind? was it really necessary to ruin his marriage after all these years? for a text message he sent to her while being sloshed. once the hangover was gone, he was ashamed for his act. couldn't he be forgiven?

a woman meets a man on a dating app, hates the way he drops hints about getting physical but ignores the remarks. she detests him she says but still goes out on a date with this rogue. the guy keeps the sexual innuendoes coming but she doesn't say a word. laughs them off. and when this guy tries to gets fresh, she presses the alarm bell. i'm wondering why she agreed to meet him when she hated him so much in the virtual world itself! isn't she the one to be blamed here? purposely asking for trouble...
.
anyway, to each his own. 
i have a hectic day ahead. so, gliding into @designerrajirm 's #kanjeevaramweek in this curious blue, green and gold one from @nallisilksarees and a chanderi brocade blouse. the jadau earrings are huge! but it's the festive season, right? .

tw: domestic violence.
üåª
üåª
üåª
i write about self love as i murder the reasons i deserve to by kind to myself, with all the reasons i am unworthy of love. i say #ibelieveher while there are moments that i still lash out at my 18-21 year old kori and question why i was stupid enough to have stayed after the first time he called me fat. the first time he called me dumb. after the first time i caught him in a lie, the first time i told myself that it was okay that he lied just this once. again and again. the first time i said no but he ended up in me anyways. the first time i asked for him to apologize and he said it was my fault. the first time i noticed that when i came into the room he jolted away from her. the first time i asked why he used to be nicer to me and he told me he was trying to win my affection, and now that he had me he didn‚Äôt have to anymore. the first time i noticed that he wanted me during sex but thought i was disgusting afterwards. the first time i let myself feel every piece of the hurt. the first time i let myself grieve where i‚Äôve been. it‚Äôs been 3 years. the trauma isn‚Äôt gone, but my self hate slowly is.  i am deserving of the care i demand others give to themselves. i am not ashamed of my moments of believing i am nothing. they are reminders that i still need reminders. that i won‚Äôt give up on myself again. self love, self acceptance and self esteem are my favorite mountain to climb. my favorite stream to wade in. my favorite breakfast to awake to eat, every morning. i‚Äôm still here, so i will keep trying. @xicanisma_ , thank you for calling me out. may we lavish ourselves in kindness. üåª

text:
i was sexually assaulted twice before i was 16. i was naive and unprepared to stand up for myself in a world where even 16 and 17 year boys have all the power. i was alone, terrified and completely unable to stop what was happening to me.
the first time i was 13 and the boy was 16. he cornered me when we were alone at his house with a few of his friends, who made it easier for him to take advantage of the situation. i said no a thousand times but he didn‚Äôt give a shit. from my perspective at the time, he wanted what he wanted and i sure as hell wasn‚Äôt going to stop him. now i realize he was just an insecure kid with zero self-control and no one teaching him or modeling respect for a female. in fact he was most likely modeled exactly what he was doing to me. 
the second time i was 15 and with someone i trusted up to that point. once again i repeatedly said no but i remember that making it even more exciting for him, like i was more of a challenging conquest. as far as he was concerned he was the only one that had the right to any decision. as i look back on it now, i can see he was probably being treated at home the way he was treating me, and there is no chance he was being taught to respect a female‚Äôs right to her body. it obviously doesn‚Äôt make it any easier but i can see the vicious cycle of example being set and subsequent behavior.
these experiences changed me forever and made intimate relationships extremely difficult for me for so long. i‚Äôm still healing and i may always be, i don‚Äôt know. 
i talk about this now for the only time i have publicly because the equivalent of both my attackers has just been confirmed into the highest court in this country. someone who does not respect a woman‚Äôs right to say no and that has violated them physically and emotionally.  someone that has scarred them forever and altered their entire representation of themselves to the world, all while denying it in his desperate race for more attention and praise from anyone that will give it. this person now has the power to make lasting decisions about how we live our lives. he has been called out and ultimately patted on the back and confirmed for his horrific, disgusting üëáüèº

text:
when so much seems so uncertain, when despair and rage fall upon you like the first bitter frost, when winter settles down into your bones like a chill you can't quite shake, when the wind speaks of all you've ever feared and lost, when the darkness hangs like ice still clinging to that stubborn, gnarled oak,

it's easy to lose faith.

most of us were told that faith is an anchor, a way to be sure and safe upon chaotic, shifting, ever-changing seas. a way of being and standing firm in an unsteady world.

it makes sense, doesn't it? the mind desperately seeks to recalibrate itself when so much remains unknown, when answers and security are cast upon the waters. when our heart and grief and disillusionment move from frozen throats to stilled tongues.

when what we thought we knew, even that which we assumed we could count upon, is taken away from us.

it's unsettling because we long to understand the "why," the reason for pain and abuse, the logic of corporate greed and filthy water and neglected, hungry children, the meaning of environmental violence and privilege and the arbitrary price of real estate, the purpose of commodifying people and dignity and justice in the name of supply and demand and order.

we long to find the center, the source, the end to the ceaseless, restless questions that brush up against our windows when we least expect them to show.

i get it. we've clung to belief and ideology because it gives us warmth in the night, because it shines and points our way to that distant, faint north star.

we sense the world leaving us behind, so we claim that we were never of it, that we belong in a time and place and reality that were far simpler, far purer than the life we can no longer recognize. we filter our pain and suffering through a sieve of destiny, an alchemy in which we become convinced that this absurdity is heading somewhere. that our investment in this broken, wounded planet is only temporary, that we can hum and whisper to ourselves of sweet nothings as the earth burns and shatters all around us.

that our disappointment can be numbed with illusion and distraction and eternal reassurances. **continued below‚¨áÔ∏è**

text:
why don‚Äôt they remember every detail? let‚Äôs talk about traumatic memory. traumatic memories differ from regular, long-term memories in the way they are stored in the brain and body when the trauma occurs and years after. while it‚Äôs happening, your body goes into flight or fight mode and your brain is hyper focused on the details that are an immediate threat to you, such as the look in the attacker‚Äôs eye, the weapon coming towards you, etc., but less prevalent details like what they were wearing and the date/time fade away because your brain is only focused on survival. stress hormones flood your system and strong surges of emotion preserve the memory even more. when those memories are triggered years after or in nightmares, they often come up in fragments, and our bodies and brains relieve the trauma and how we felt all over again. 
it is also very important to note that there have been studies on traumatized brains while triggered and the main speech centers of the brain shut down. this makes it increasingly more difficult to talk about the trauma in-depth (bessel van der kolk, m.d., the body keeps the score, 2014). this a very high-level overview. i‚Äôm not a doctor or therapist. tough as milk is a yoga program committed to providing trauma-informed care and that starts (and continues) with education about our brain and body on trauma. there has been extensive research done on this subject in recent years, educate yourself and help educate others when they make inaccurate remarks about survivors. #domesticviolenceawareness #believesurvivors
name: Tough as Milk
tweet_full:
why don‚Äôt they remember every detail? let‚Äôs talk about traumatic memory. traumatic memories differ from regular, long-term memories in the way they are stored in the brain and body when the trauma occurs and years after. while it‚Äôs happening, your body goes into flight or fight mode and your brain is hyper focused on the details that are an immediate threat to you, such as the look in the attacker‚Äôs eye, the weapon coming towards you, etc., but less prevalent details like what they were wearing and the date/time fade away because your brain is only focused on survival. stress hormones flood your system and strong surges of emotion preserve the memory even more. when those memories are triggered years after or in nightmares, they often come up in fragments, and our bodies and brains relieve the trauma and how we felt all over again. 
it is also very important to note that there have been studies on traumatized brains while triggered and the main speech centers of the brain shut down. this makes it increasingly more difficult to talk about the trauma in-depth (bessel van der kolk, m.d., the body keeps the score, 2014). this a very high-level overview. i‚Äôm not a doctor or therapist. tough as milk is a yoga program committed to providing trauma-informed care and that starts (and continues) with education about our brain and body on trauma. there has been extensive research done on this subject in recent years, educate yourself and help educate others when they make inaccurate remarks about survivors. #domesticviolenceawareness #believesurvivors

text:
in the wake of the kavanaugh scandal and the high profile #metoo cases that have gone global, it's important that we remind ourselves about the power of consent.
.
if it's not a yes, then it's a no.
if he/she does not voice their desire to continue with you in any form or relationship, it's a no.
take it that way and do not force yourself on another human being.
boys are raped and girls are raped.
and irrespective of the excuse, rape is rape.
sexual assault is sexual assault.
harassment, catcalling- these things are what they are.
call evil by its name.
let's stop enabling criminals by beating around the bush.
no response is a response in itself.
take the hint.

text:
america. oh america. this past month has taught me much. "why didn't she cone forward sooner?!" "there's too many inconsistencies in her story! she must be a liar!" "the democrats are just trying to stall progress!" are the screams. 
yet.
when i came forward, you wrote me off as an attention seeker. when i came forward, i was told i was lying. when i can forward, no one cared. 
others like me, we see how you respond to women like dr. ford and the #metoo movement. and we hide back in silence because our friends, our family, our everyone are the ones screaming. 
i am one of the one in four women who are sexually assaulted once in her life. 
i am one of your friends & your neighbors i am your daughter, your sister, your cousin. 
america, when will you learn?
#metoo #timesup #istandwithher #sheisme #america #kavanaugh

text:
it is okay to feel like trauma is the grieving of a version of yourself that died. it is okay to feel the grief of that loss. that grief won't always behave the same. it's unpredictability will shake you. however, the ability to keep moving forward in spite of your grief, is resilience. resilience isn't tied up with a neat bow. it often takes an immense amount of trauma to illustrate the resilience an individual has in coping. accept yourself where you are at. be empathetic to yourself. healing is not linear. it ebbs and flows between moments of intense fear, sadness and even empowerment. you are entitled to those emotions. sending you all love.üíú
.

text: no one could ever touch who i really am in this life.  no matter what happens to me, i am still the same authentic person i was born to be.  i still carry love and peace as my true nature.  every human is born with the same capacity to love.  i was misguided along the way, yet found my way back to my heart by way of the 12 step rooms, lots of loving sponsors and staying sober and clean.  my life got easier because my perspective on life changed.  my heart opened and i began to open up to others and become ruthlessly honest with myself about all areas of my life.  i realized i used to keep people in my life that told me what i wanted to hear as friends.  now i surround myself with those who challenge me and live in their own integrity.  drinking is not an option for me and facing all of my issues from my past just adds to the remarkable loving human i am becoming.  i believe my best attributes are humility and vulnerability.  this allows me to admit when i need help and to be resilient in life.  i am learning how to help others by allowing my heart to be guided.  i would not trade anything that happened in my life because it all adds up to who i am today.  all the abuse in my past has made me the woman i have become.  i am here with a message and to stop this from continuing for another generation.  i hope you will help me by spreading the word. #metooneveryou #metoo #timesup #sobrietyismylife #sobrietyrocks #sobriety #attitudeofgratitude #aa #onedayatatime #billw #drfordismyhero #believeher #soberwomen #soberwomen #sexualtrauma

if the last couple weeks have gotten to you, like so many of us, and you feel overwhelmed, disheartened, angry, and/or powerless, please reach out, talk to someone and take care of yourself. also, yoga is a beautiful way to both simultaneously soothe and empower yourself. while i‚Äôm partial to mountains (since i grew up near them), don‚Äôt overestimate the power that mountain pose (tadasana) can have. .
.
.
1) stand with heels slightly apart. lift and spread your toes and the balls of your feet, then lay them softly down on the floor. you may try to count and connect each toe if feeling really overwhelmed with emotion. rock back and forth and side to side. gradually reduce this swaying to a standstill, with your weight balanced evenly on the feet.
.
.
2) engage your upper legs and  lift the knee caps. lift the inner ankles to strengthen the inner arches, then imagine a line of energy all the way up from inner ankles and from there through the core of your torso, neck, and head, and out through the crown of your head. take deep breaths in and out as you imagine this line of calming yet powerful energy run up and down you. . .
.
3) press your shoulder blades into your back then widen them across and release them down your back, acknowledging the power you have within. lift the top of your sternum straight toward the sky. become expansive. hang your arms loosely beside the torso.
.
4) continue smooth, deep diaphragmatic breathing, repeating an affirmation such as any of the following: .
.
my voice matters. 
i matter. 
i can reach out to those who understand. 
i am powerful, no matter what anyone says or does. 
i reclaim myself. .
.
#yogatherapy #yogaeverydamnday #therapy #mantra #affirmation #selfcare #enoughisenough #believesurvivors #metoo #govote

text:
üôåüèº #exactly #payattention #believewomen #empowerment #howto ‚Äî the #metoo movement, in addition to raising awareness, has given people the courage to speak up about the times they've been wronged, harassed, or assaulted. women around the world have spoken out and there are horror stories from everywhere.
‚Äî
the majority of sexual assaults are not reported to the police
-
only 310 out of every 1,000 sexual assaults are reported to police. that means about 2 out of 3 go unreported.
-
individuals of college-age:
‚Ä¢ female students: 20% report
‚Ä¢ female non-students: 32% report
the elderly: 28% report
members of the military:
‚Ä¢ 43% of female victims
‚Ä¢ 10% of male victims reported.
-
reasons victims choose to report‚Äîor not
-
of the sexual violence crimes reported to police from 2005-2010, the survivor reporting gave the following reasons for doing so:
-
‚Ä¢ 28% to protect the household or victim from further crimes by the offender
‚Ä¢ 25% to stop the incident or prevent recurrence or escalation
‚Ä¢ 21% to improve police surveillance or they believed they had a duty to do so
‚Ä¢ 17% to catch/punish/prevent offender from reoffending
‚Ä¢ 6% gave a different answer, or declined to cite one reason
‚Ä¢ 3% did so to get help or recover loss
-
of the sexual violence crimes not reported to police from 2005-2010, the victim gave the following reasons for not reporting:
-
‚Ä¢ 20% feared retaliation
‚Ä¢ 13% believed the police would not do anything to help
‚Ä¢ 13% believed it was a personal matter
‚Ä¢ 8% reported to a different official
‚Ä¢ 8% believed it was not important enough to report
‚Ä¢ 7% did not want to get the perpetrator in trouble
‚Ä¢ 2% believed the police could not do anything to help
‚Ä¢ 30% gave another reason, or did not cite one reason
‚Äî

text:
after all the tension from last week, as a survivor, i understood so well the fear of not being believed, the guilt that somehow it was my fault, the self betrayal i felt for not reaching out for help sooner. it never feels real until it's said outloud. though it's been years, random things still catch me off guard as the details come rushing back.
.
whenever my soul feels weary i always gravitate towards nature. it's a place to not think of anything and to let all my senses out to play. this day more than most, i felt like i had to go out and do something physical to remind myself that i am my own, and like the seasons that turn so gracefully, hard times will be followed by growth and light if only we allow ourselves to let go.
.
i'm grateful for the resilient women around me and the men who listen without opinions. although the responses have been all over the spectrum, i am floored by the solidarity that women have shown each other and the humbleness and learning that some men have responded with.
. 
as an adult, i wondered what it would've been like if i had a voice back then. more than anything, i owe it to my younger self to be an open ear for the vulnerable and to be that voice that says, "i believe you." to become the exact person i needed during my darkest times for someone else, would and has made all the difference.

_________________________________

text: where change is made and laws are passed. a judge once told me that i may have to take a trip to ottawa to change the law when i was speaking about my case. it's very difficult to prove crown misconduct and they are not liable for being negligent and do have the discretion to stay charges as long as their reasons are absent of bias and misconduct. depending on the results of my judicial review, i may be headed there next year to try and change the law. i have received so many emails from other women who have had the same thing happen to them with crowns blocking the prosecution and staying the charges for no real good reason, without any evidence even being heard, because of their opinion on a woman's credibility, laziness and unwillingness to put in the extra work to clear any complexities surrounding the victim, protecting police who forget about the case or even wanting to protect the perpetrator, when there were grounds. i believe that the honourable judges in ontario should be the gatekeeper, not the crown, when victims of crimes, especially women who come forward with evidence wishing to press charges for sexual assault or harassment. crowns and police can engage in msiconduct or negligence. its important that a judge is the decision maker on a woman's credibility and that all the evidence is heard by an unbiased judge or jury. right now, crowns and police hold the power. if they don't pursue the case, you can't move forward. this is why women should just pursue a civil law suit against their alleged perpetrators where they will get to go in front of a judge and present their evidence. everyone deserves justice and closure and a civil case is the best way to do this without being embarassed and scrutinized by the police and crowns, risking your good character and credibility being stripped away. how can preventing a woman from telling her story in court for any other reason than the context of the incident not be bias? only an honourable judge can determine the merits. ‚ù§‚ù§‚ù§ #justice #ontario #socialjusticeforwomen #socialjustice #humanrights #crown #law #womensrights #sexualharassment #sexualassault #metoo #whyididntreport #ottawa #canada #toronto

text: if you haven‚Äôt read lydia‚Äôs story about the brutal sexual abuse she endured then please do, i‚Äôll post a link in my profile. it‚Äôs a story to often told and too often repeated. women have been silenced too long and honestly it‚Äôs time for the pendulum to swing the other way and i hope it swings really, really far. personally, the dialogue and awareness that has been happening has deeply affected me, because i too have my own story, i too was not believed. it still hurts. this isn‚Äôt only a woman‚Äôs issue. it‚Äôs humanity issue and i stand with those who are oppressed, those who have been silenced and those who have been abused whether it be man, woman or child. i swear i will teach my boys how to defend women and i will teach my daughter how to defend herself, how to yell, scream, kick and say no and be proud of it. but more so i will teach all three of them the history of women and other oppressed people. i will teach them how abhorrent our past has been so that they can change the future and until they do i‚Äôll be blazing the trail for them. peace to all you sisters and brother who have been through this. much love...üíî

text:
conference announcement // we have just confirmed that katarina carroll, australia's first ever female fire & emergency services commissioner will speak at mate's #besomeonewhodoessomething conference. before becoming the commissioner, katarina was the operations commander of australia's biggest peacetime operation - the g20 - where she was in command of over 6,500 police officers and security personal, tasked with keeping world leaders and royalty safe. something katarina calls a career highlight.

katarina joins a stellar conference line up of amazing women using their voices to redefine a new normal in a post #metoo era, a new standard of inclusion and equality. this is what we have been waiting for, this is the social movement we all want to be a part of. we are honoured that mate will host women as spectacular as commissioner katarina carroll, to amplify the ground-breaking rumblings of #metoo and #timesup and solidify the place of the bystander as integral to this movement.

#dosomething #genderequality #genderbasedviolence #conference

for those who believe there is a war against men right now, ummm, find the nearest bridge and jump off of it. and of course i'm kidding...(not really), but let me explain. men: have you ever sexually assaulted or harassed a woman? no? okay, then you have less than a 0.0003% chance of being accused of doing that. that's a real number. men have a greater chance of getting sexually assaulted than getting accused of sexual assault. get the absolute fuck out of here with your "it's a scary time being a man right now" horseshit. oh really? as scary as leaving an earbud out when you're walking/running so you can hear people approach you? as scary as gripping your keys to use as a weapon when you're walking to your car late at night? as scary as having to avoid taking an uber/lyft/cab alone? as scary as paying close attention to your drink to make sure no one puts anything in it? as scary as going to the restroom in pairs to avoid getting cornered? as scary as avoiding solo dates because you don't know what might happen? as scary as keeping a wary eye on men when they walk by you (my ass has been groped by two separate strangers on two separate occasions when i was simply walking down the street ‚úåÔ∏è)? goddamn it's so frustrating. if people put half the time and energy they spent attacking accusers and worrying about men being wrongly accused (men are and have been fucking fine for hundreds of years by the way) into actually protecting and respecting and believing and supporting women, we wouldn't have so many fucking problems. so if you truly believe there's a war against men going on right now, you're part of the problem. the war is against liars and abusers and manipulators and harassers and bullies and rapists and murderers. why is this so hard to understand? does it hurt your small brain? or is the problem that you don't have one? #metoo

text_retweet:
we need braver conversations around sensitive issues such as #metoo, racism, colonialism, indifference.  it seems everywhere you turn, there is heightened emotions that are fuelled by hate and fear. we need to tell our stories in a way that brings people together, not create further lines of division.  we need to be able to navigate these conversations with wisdom and skill that will strengthen connection between people and people groups, not fortify dividing walls. 
this is what we are seeking to do with our show rewritten nov  16-17. 
facing hard stuff head on with courage, compassion and community. 
oh, the demons that we fight with. self hate, doubt, fear. where do they come from?
.
.
.
what creates us? what joys and sorrows reveal the culture and people we are presently? join us as we dive deeply into issues of sex, relationships, racism, colonialism, and a hope to be rewritten.
.
.
.

text:
what is domestic violence?

domestic violence (also called intimate partner violence (ipv), domestic abuse or relationship abuse) is a pattern of behaviors used by one partner to maintain power and control over another partner in an intimate relationship.

domestic violence does not discriminate. anyone of any race, age, sexual orientation, religion or gender can be a victim ‚Äì or perpetrator ‚Äì of domestic violence. it can happen to people who are married, living together or who are dating. it affects people of all socioeconomic backgrounds and education levels.

domestic violence includes behaviors that physically harm, arouse fear, prevent a partner from doing what they wish or force them to behave in ways they do not want. it includes the use of physical and sexual violence, threats and intimidation, emotional abuse and economic deprivation. many of these different forms of domestic violence/abuse can be occurring at any one time within the same intimate relationship. #domesticviolenceawareness #domesticabuse #intimatepartnerviolence #intimatepartnerabuse #intimatepartnerawarwnessmonth #october #purpleribbon #survivors #womenyourareappreciated #metoo #metoomovement

she looks like me: standing with her hand raised, praying for the strength to tell the truth. she looks like me, somehow under fire, labeled as a liar for what she can‚Äôt prove...but we all know in our bones, you can‚Äôt fake a pain like that. she‚Äôs under attack, and all i can see, is what you‚Äôre thinking, too... she looks like me.‚Äù

text:
every day, you have an opportunity to create, who you are and who you want to be. 
so choose wisely on who you surround yourself with and the voices you listen to. 
we don‚Äôt have to be victims of circumstances. 
we can intentionally create & craft the person we have always wanted to be! 
but this takes effort & intention, day in and day out.  greatness does not happen on accident, it is created on purpose!! this was one of the greatest news for me coming out of abuse, i got to choose a new me!  i could redefine whoever i wanted to be, and daily, purposefully walk in that direction! 
my sweet friend, choose-victor, instead of victim. ‚Ä¢

text:
grateful.

i filed a #police report today against my rapist.

__

for the first time in weeks, i feel peace. i can think clearly. i have hope. i'm grateful for law enforcement.

__

as noted, sexual encounters involving deceit as a way to obtain ‚Äúconsent‚Äù may not in fact be consensual. jed rubenfeld argues for the stronger view that all sex by deception is non-consensual and therefore counts as rape. as he puts it, ‚Äòsex-by-deception is always sex without consent, because a consent obtained by deception, as courts have long and repeatedly held outside of rape law, is ‚Äúno consent‚Äù at all‚Äô (2012-2013: 2). __

text:
last week a male client asked me if "women would ever get it?" i was confused... he explained that he meant would women will ever find a way to join together in order to really yield the power they are capable of having. he didn‚Äôt understand why women always seemed to be pitted against each other. 
i explained to him that we're taught that we have to compete for everything. that 
only some women are valuable, that only some women will get the attention or the 
praise or the message that they matter that they're worthy of love and respect.
 and that those women whom we've been led to believe do matter, not only typically act a certain way around and toward men, they also typically "don‚Äôt make a scene", "play nice" and, of course, fit into the cultural standards of beauty. 
we are taught that not every woman is important but if you look the "right way" and act the "right way" you have a better chance at being important. so we compete. we envy. we literally make ourselves the smallest because we have been taught that this is what 
is important. tell me ladies, when you‚Äôre completely engulfed with counting 
calories, macronutrients, carbs or grams of sugar, how much do world affairs or 
politics really matter to you? what about your right to protect yourself and the right 
to make decisions about your own body? not that much? that‚Äôs right. while we‚Äôre 
busy competing with each other over having the smoothest skin or the perfect ass or the smallest waist or the cutest outfit, the guys are out there taking all the power. 
the real power. 
like my client asked - when will be get it? when we compete over things like this 
we all lose. i‚Äôm not saying that you need to stop wearing make-up or grow out your 
armpit hair (unless you want to), what i‚Äôm saying is that it‚Äôs time we all woke up. 
we all matter. we are all essential to make change happen. our children depend on it and our country depends on it. step away from the competition and embrace the woman next to you for who she is. let go of jealousy. there is enough self-worth for every single one of us. 
#womensupportingwomen #metoo #youareenough #riseup #bopo #fuckyourbeautystandards #bodypositive

the #metoo and #timesup movements might only have broken out in the last 12 months, but a thread connects the silence breakers of today with those of decades ago. and none is more prominent that marilyn monroe, who's often remembered instead for the more salacious details of her personal life and the rumors that she slept her way to the top. but as early as 1953, when monroe was just a rising star in hollywood, she penned an article called 'wolves i have known,' for the first time exposing hollywood's toxic environment for women by detailing multiple examples of harassment by and propositions from unnamed men. ‚Äúthere are many types of wolves,‚Äù she wrote. ‚Äúsome are sinister, others are just good-time charlies trying to get something for nothing and others make a game of it.‚Äù she would later say in an interview that as an aspiring model and actress, sex "was like part of the job ‚Ä¶ and if you didn‚Äôt go along, there were 25 girls who would.‚Äù but in the years after her death, monroe‚Äôs biographers, largely men, tended to ignore the star‚Äôs silence-breaking role.
.
did you know that, @chancetherapper and ye?
.
to learn more about monroe's "wolves" and how she fought against them, follow the link in our bio to listen to the thread, ozy's award-winning podcast that exposes the hidden connections between some of the most famous names in history.
.
.

#dailywisdom ... i have carried the memory of those five boys and that afternoon for twenty-four years,¬†reviewing it over and over (when i could finally admit my assault to my therapist and indeed myself), feeling the¬†shame¬†and the self-blame every time. it has been a¬†burden,¬†the weight of which i¬†can now acknowledge. i hid behind my secret. i didn‚Äôt have to speak in front of an international audience. i was never cross examined. my assailants, whose names i never knew, apparently never became famous nor vied for important positions of trust. i miss having the opportunity to bring those boys to justice. if you have a story about assault,¬†please share it. these conversations cannot stop. add your own in whatever way feels right to you. talk to a friend, a therapist, a¬†spiritual¬†counselor. make a poem. write a song. don‚Äôt worry about the holes in your story. they are part of your story as they are part of mine. memory is inherently unreliable. with time, it degrades. with trauma, it fragments. in isolation, it festers, bursting out at inopportune times, creating¬†nightmares, and fueling an enduring sense of¬†fear¬†and anxiety. this is such a paradox. the more we resist talking about our¬†memories¬†of assault, the longer they persist and the more power they have over our lives. ¬†when we tell our stories, we reclaim our power,¬†help ourselves and¬†help each other. #metoo #wetoo #strength #courage #believewomen #believemen #believesurvivors #ibelievesurvivors #supportsurvivors #isupportsurvivors #standwithsurvivors #istandwithsurvivors

text:
with the #metoo movement having sort of an uprising in india right now, the issue of sexual harassment has been on my mind. more often than not the victim is blamed for wearing certain kinds of clothes. shorts, mini skirts, plunging necklines etc. .
when i was in india everytime i got dressed i had to think 'is this ok to wear to a certain place?' 'is this too body-hugging?' 'is this too short?' luckily for the past few years, these questions have never crossed my mind while getting ready for the day. so yesterday, after i shot this look i had to go to a body shop to get my car's smog test done. i didn't even think twice about what i was wearing. as soon as, i reached the shop i felt a lot of eyes on me. as i walked in wearing this skirt & sweater i heard whistles, cat-calling. #ignoremodeon i went in and asked the owner if they performed smog tests, he said that it was next door and needed to pull into the next door. as i was walking out, two guys came into the shop and gave me the 'top-down scan'! they went to the owner and said 'man how can you let her go, you gotta service her!' and i felt so dirty. i just walked off and took my car to the next door. .
it didn't affect me because unfortunately, i have (like most women) gotten used to it. the point is its not the clothes that the victim wears it's the eyes and the mind of the predator that needs changing. we don't need the girls to change the way they dress, we need the boys and men to change the way they think and look!

text:
sexual harassment, abuse, and assault can and do have traumatic impacts on our bodies, minds, and spirits. living in a culture that doesn‚Äôt respect or see women as fully human, a culture that objectifies us, a culture that constantly tells us how we are less than, and our bodies are not our own but are only meant for the pleasure of men exacerbates our trauma and has us living in a highly activated state.¬† as a part of our personal trauma processing journey we need to learn how to regulate our nervous systems so they work as they are meant to, how to connect to our physiological boundaries and reclaim our bodies as our own, find our own ways to center and ground, and acknowledge, embrace, and grow our internal and external resources.¬† this work allows us to be more intentional, mindful, and compassionate in our own lives and in the world, to focus our rage and pain in appropriate and helpful ‚Äì instead of damaging (to ourselves & our relationships) ‚Äì ways, and move from surviving to thriving as a way of being within ourselves and in the world.

in order for us to create a world where women feel safe walking down the street alone, safe in their own homes, safe in their own bodies, we need to be able to remain calm in challenging situations, to speak our truth without malice, to have compassion for ourselves and others who have had similar experiences and come together in true community, we need to have practical tools to calm our systems and the true understanding that we are not alone.

for more info and sliding scale pricing you can visit:

http://gwynnraimondi.com/tieforsexualtrauma/
/../
#sexualtrauma #traumainformed #sexualassault #sexualabuse #sexualharassment #complextrauma #metoo #timesup #timesupnow

text:
anyone who knows me, knows that i am rarely speechless, but since saturday‚Äôs confirmation hearing that‚Äôs exactly how i‚Äôve felt: speechless. 
yet, my emotions have evolved from the void and empty initial reaction to fear, then sadness, and next anger. now, i‚Äôve landed in this place of just wishing i could do something good.
in trying to find a positive way to veer these evolving and revolving emotions, i saw that people were writing letters of support and appreciation to christine blasey ford...i decided to do just that. i sat down, and wrote a letter to dr. ford to thank her. 
for her strength.
for her courage.
for her bravery.
and, for starting the waves of change. 
thank you, christine.

text:
spiritual abuse is a tricky thing. your abuser can use the bible,  torah or qu'ran against you. they can manipulate passages to make them  fit their sadistic plans. god given words are never meant to be used  against you to make you have sex (rape) against your will, be hit or  give all your money to your abuser. those thoughts and ideals are  manipulative and should not be invoked on you. forcing you into a  religion is a form of spiritual abuse. married or not you can chose your  religion (although with marriage there should be a discussion). if your  leader is enforcing the poor behavior of your abuser, that is spiritual  abuse. your leader should recognize abuse and should be able to convey  that to the abuser and help them get their life on track. you don't have  to settle for spiritual abuse because that's what "the bible" says.
.

text:
absolutely loved nine perfect strangers by liane moriarty. although the story is told from the perspective of 12 different characters, it was incredibly easy to follow. the story touches on several modern day issues including the #metoo movement, depression, suicide, grief and self-loathing. but don‚Äôt be fooled, there‚Äôs lots of humour as well. i think every reader will be able to relate to one, if not multiple characters. it was overall a very easy and relaxing read that didn‚Äôt require much concentration which is exactly what i needed after reading the clockmaker‚Äôs daughter.
.
.
ps i now have two new book sleeve designs on my etsy website. link in bio.

text: a few years ago, i was at plein bois camping with friends. a group of french guys set up camp next to us soon after we arrived. my friend - who is very sociable - struck up a conversation with them. (i don‚Äôt speak french) one of the guys, a very bearish¬†‚Äúthicc‚Äù type took an instant, obvious liking to me. it was uncomfortable to be near him, he was so obviously into me.¬† the day progressed and we didn‚Äôt see them again until evening. everyone was drinking and having a good time. around 1 am, i left my friends to go to sleep. i don‚Äôt remember much up to the leaving part. i remember leaving my friends and getting a little lost in the twists and turns. when i finally found our campsite, the french guys camp was busy with a party. i got in my tent and into my sleeping bag. as i was about to nod off, i heard someone stumble into my tent, speaking drunken, slurred french. i instantly recognized his voice as the guy from earlier. i zipped the sleeping bag up over my head and held onto the zipper. it was the guy from earlier. he was clearly wasted. i could hear him fumbling with his belt buckle, shoving his pants down before laying next to me and started feeling me up through the sleeping bag, humping me through the sleeping bag. i held onto the zipper and lay on my stomach. he kept saying things in french. he was rough and trying desperately to find an opening. i held on and lay there, not moving. in retrospect, i was terrified. he was quite a bit bigger than me and could have gotten in, if he weren‚Äôt so drunk.¬† it was difficult to breathe in my sleeping bag but i held onto that zipper. after about five minutes, he became frustrated and left. i waited for what seemed like forever until my friends finally came back. i could hear the french party going on for a few more hours.

text:
with all that is happening in the world in the past year...with events such as the #metoo movement, dr. ford's testimony against brett kavanaugh, and taylor's very public trial against david mueller... i wanted to make today's post not about a specific woman, but... to the women who have come forward about their sexual assault. to the women who have come forward about their experiences with sexual harassment. to the women who have faced the person who has assaulted them in court. to the women who haven't come forward because they are scared of what people will say. to the women who feel like they have to suffer in silence. to the women who may not have experienced these particular events but are supporting and helping in any way they can women who have. to the women who keep fighting every day for their rights. to the women giving a voice to women everywhere. 
from the bottom of my heart, thank you. we all need to do our part to make the world a better place. anyone reading this...please share in the comments what organizations you like supporting when it comes to these issues. i would love to help in any way i can. ‚ù§
.
.

text: at least 30 schoolgirls were sent to the hospital on saturday after defending themselves against a group of teenage boys who had been sexually harassing them in bihard, india. police say that after the girls fought back ‚Äì with words, and, eventually, physically ‚Äì some boys returned with their parents and beat them up. india was ranked the most dangerous country for sexual violence against women earlier this year and is currently dealing with its own #metoo movement.

text:
in indonesia, un women works alongside local ngos to deliver their flagship safe cities program. the safe cities program works to reduce harassment and violence against women and girls by making cities safe spaces for women and girls, through safe public transport, community training and strengthened legislation to protect women and girls. the prumpung area was selected along with two other sites in jakarta to pilot to program in indonesia, due to high prevalence of violence experienced. according to the national women‚Äôs commission, there were over 250,000 cases of violence against women and girls reported in indonesia in 2016. üì∑: un women/ryan brown
-

text:
usually my running is an exuberant experience, but today? today i ran to take the edge off my rage. hearing the human hemorrhoid in the white house  apologized to an alleged abuser on behalf of the nation he is supposed to represent who tried to hold him accountable has caused my rage to rise to an unhealthy level.

so fuck that abscessed hemorrhoid who stole the presidency. fuck the state and local elected officials who didn't fight like hell for the will of the people screaming for justice. and fuck every one of you who supported this decision. i was raped many years ago now, and although most days i can shrug off that fact, this process is personal to me, and has brought a lot of things to the surface that i'm trying to exorcise. to those of you out there similarly hurting, i love you. it's okay to retreat when it's needed. there are others out there who want to help shoulder your burden. and we. will. keep. fighting.

text:
"all the women in me are tired." -nayyirah waheed.

the woman who is shamed for her fierce independence and success is tired. 
the woman who loves to receive affection, but is called too needy is tired.
the woman who is called a bitch for standing up for herself is tired.
the woman who practices endless patience and gentleness, yet called "a doormat" is tired.
the woman who has been told her brilliant fire and sexuality is wrong is tired.
the woman labeled a prude for being modest is tired.
the woman who was taught her only value came from her beauty is tired.
the little girl, the wild child, who is scolded for being "too much" is tired.
the woman who is classy and sophisticated, but seen as "stuck up" is tired.
the woman who loves men but has been traumatized by men is tired.
the woman who needs sisterhood in her life, but has been so damaged by other women is tired.
the woman who would give it all for her partner for nothing in return is tired.
the woman who is single and facing the world on her own is tired.
the woman who still has hope for her country is tired.
the woman who longs for a tribe by her side is tired.
the woman who is her own hero is tired.

but let me tell you something about these women. something that you might not fully realize. when we get tired, we don't stay down forever. we won't stay collapsed or defeated forever. when we are tired, we get fed up. we rise again with the whole damn fire. hell hath no fury like a woman scorned. just you wait. .
.
.

text:
the grief is real! letting go of everything you know to walk forward into the unknown is scary! re-wiring ever part of your make up knowing you can never go back or more the fact of knowing you will never want to go back. getting to know myself on this level has been such a hard journey - discovering all the pieces of myself that i have thrown out and disowned a long the journey of life as i labelled them as not good enough. having to pick up those pieces and love them again! going back to basics and being ok with the loneliness of not belonging. i understand my journey and at times it is so hard to accept the challenges i face daily and so many times i want to give up, and so many times i break and so many times i shed tears and so many times i want to retreat back into old coping mechanisms - but fuck no!!! i have so much more to give, to share, to love, to live, to achieve, to create ! i will never retreat back into the shell of a person i was just to make myself and others feel comfortable! my priority is me as the more i love myself the more space i can create to love others üíïüå∏üôè xx candice zita 
#theloveitmovement #mystory #inspire #iwanttomakeadifference #selflove #grief #heal #transformationtuesday #iloveme #bebrave #courage #shine #achieve #succeed #entrepreneur #iamok #iamworthy #metoo
name: Candice Zita

text:
feeling rotten again today and i‚Äôm sure, just like everyone else, that it‚Äôs the reason i feel pretty low too.
my head has been stuck on woodford whether remembering the scary guy who lived in the room opposite (i was genuinely frightened of him on several occasions and afraid to return home many times), the sleep paralysis after the bad thing happened when the tiny man in the next room would wake up at 5am each morning and put old westerns on his tv, the times i got home drunk from islington after work because i didn‚Äôt know how to stop the thoughts in my head and would say the wrong thing or do the wrong thing because i felt so wrong and didn‚Äôt know how to be right or any former or even future version of me. 
everything had been stripped from me (and not just from the joker faced guy in the club) and though i have felt more alone since then, i was literally on my own at that point. 
i have hated thinking of it but when looking for a photo of the view from the bedroom window there, a window i looked out of any time i had a bad thought cross my mind or when i wanted to stop thinking (it was mesmerising, even if that view holds bad memories too), i stumbled across this photo.
the fran bench which was also known at one point as jr and i‚Äôs bench. i have so many lovely and gorgeous memories of spending time in the light and dark of the park with friends and a loved one. this picture has put some nice memories of london and the people i was close to into my head, i love remembering the good times. i hope to make more some day but i‚Äôm still trying to heal. healing takes time and i need to own that i need to heal.

my head has been stuck on woodford whether remembering the scary guy who lived in the room opposite (i was genuinely frightened of him on several occasions and afraid to return home many times), the sleep paralysis after the bad thing happened when the tiny man in the next room would wake up at 5am each morning and put old westerns on his tv, the times i got home drunk from islington after work because i didn‚Äôt know how to stop the thoughts in my head and would say the wrong thing or do the wrong thing because i felt so wrong and didn‚Äôt know how to be right or any former or even future version of me. 
everything had been stripped from me (and not just from the joker faced guy in the club) and though i have felt more alone since then, i was literally on my own at that point. 
i have hated thinking of it but when looking for a photo of the view from the bedroom window there, a window i looked out of any time i had a bad thought cross my mind or when i wanted to stop thinking (it was mesmerising, even if that view holds bad memories too), i stumbled across this photo.
the fran bench which was also known at one point as jr and i‚Äôs bench. i have so many lovely and gorgeous memories of spending time in the light and dark of the park with friends and a loved one. this picture has put some nice memories of london and the people i was close to into my head, i love remembering the good times. i hope to make more some day but i‚Äôm still trying to heal. healing takes time and i need to own that i need to heal.

text: body shaming....you don‚Äôt have to be a celebrity to be shamed by society. i have been a group fitness instructor for 2 years now. i am a human being just like everyone else. i have cravings, i am a mom, i have other jobs, i fluctuate in my weight, i have cellulite, i get pimples, etc.... my journey is never ending. each day i have to put on a smile and serve others ( no complaints btw), i have to keep a professional energy and pretend i am never tired.  my classes are not even my workout it‚Äôs my job to make sure the members of the gym are in proper form and keep them motivated. not to mention getting my own workout in. i have done a ironman and gotten super skinny from the training and now i have gained 25lbs by not training and people want to shame my body! shame on you! i am secure in my ‚Äúcellulite and fat rolls‚Äù i love my curves and my ability to have had 2 beautiful children and not to mention 44 years old. so if you see a group fitness instructor maybe a little over weight try not to judge what she looks like, maybe give her a high five from beating what she has been through!!!! how about lifting one another up instead of stomping their heart! rant over.........love, a group fitness instructor ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
i wrote this song about a year ago and it‚Äôs crazy how emotional it still makes me feel. (this is about halfway through - link in bio if you want to watch the whole thing.)
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i just want to speak my piece and say that never in history has it not been a ‚Äúscary time‚Äù for women. i‚Äôll give you a few examples of survival tactics we are taught at a very young age that won‚Äôt be found in a text book...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Ä¢always park under streetlights.
‚Ä¢put a key between your fingers when you walk home alone, just incase it should turn into a weapon.
‚Ä¢never set your drink down.
‚Ä¢travel in packs and never go to the bathroom alone.
‚Ä¢never let it slip in casual conversation when you‚Äôll be home alone.
‚Ä¢don‚Äôt wear jewelry with your name on it.
‚Ä¢check the backseat of the car and lock the doors as soon as you get inside.
‚Ä¢make sure to tell someone if you go out for a run. you know, just incase...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it‚Äôs sad, because i recently broke down and got pepper spray and you don‚Äôt even understand how much safer it makes me feel now. like, every woman out there reading this, i urge you to go spend the five dollars. because to me, it means that it might just save my life one day.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
these are the survival tactics that have been passed down for generations, from mother to daughter to granddaughter. this is the reality we accept. no one can tell me that these aren‚Äôt the unspoken truths of what it‚Äôs like to navigate the world as a woman.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
on an ideological level, we have got to redefine the way we view sexual harassment, assault, and sexism. for anyone out there living in black and white, i urge you to take your rose-colored glasses off, read a book, listen to some music, and be a part of the change that wants this world to be a safer and fairer place. #metoo #metoomovement #behindthemetoos #standforsomething #orfallforanything #useyourvoice #bobdylan #joanbaez #jonimitchell #unitedwestand #proudamerican #grabembythemidterms #vote #scvotes #civicduty #freedom #bethechange #millenials #womenempowerment #womensupportwomen #womensupportingwomen #believesurvivors #believewomen

text:
i healed to let survivors know that it is okay to vent and share their pain here on this page. because when we shut down and silence ourselves the damage of the trauma continues to hurt or destroy survivors. when i was hurting, i never had the opportunity to have a platform or a safe place like this to share my pain or the betrayal of my family. i was one of the first pioneers to create a safe place for survivors to vent and come forward with the sexual abuse.

i also healed to let other survivors know that we can find balance ‚Äúheal‚Äù and find happiness because i have found peace and happiness.

yes in spite of the memories and the flashbacks i am happy. 
recently i have had many disagreements on our page about our post and that‚Äôs okay.  everyone is entitled to their opinion, but we will continue our mission to spread awareness and to provide a safe place for others survivors to vent and heal from childhood sexual abuse.

i want to thank everyone that supports our page. 
thank you for allowing us to share our hearts and our hopes of someday ending this horrific crime with this movement dedicated to adult survivors of childhood sexual abuse.

cecibel contreras 
founder
harold glen hull
president 
isuvoa.com

text:
to all of those who reached out to me last night and this morning - i thank you. your love and concern has helped me more than you know. and to those generous and brave enough to share your stories with me - i am beyond privileged that you confided in me and will keep your truths with me always.
.
further from my post last night, i have pushed through. that‚Äôs not to say that i‚Äôm okay today, but i‚Äôm better than i was. i‚Äôm not holding high expectations that i will be 100% by the end of the day. or week. or month. but i‚Äôm getting there.
.
i‚Äôm giving myself permission to heal. no matter how slowly that might be.
.
if you‚Äôre struggling with something, give yourself permission to fail. failing is okay. it‚Äôs how we learn. failing is part of life. we all move at our own pace. it will get better, one step at a time, if you allow it.
.
.

text:
had a conversation with @lydiala  this morning, who suggested this exactly. 
we are dear friends who have known each other more than 20 years and yet, we have not fully shared our traumas, the ones we are working to silently heal from. 
there are the big ones that are too hard to bring voice to. and the ones where you feel at fault. the ones that were just a ‚Äòsmall thing‚Äô. and those that are blocked from memory by the depths of the wound. 
there is a time and a place i hear you say. yes, there is, but there is also now. 
women, call your women and let‚Äôs talk about it. time to get raw and real and heal with each other. we heal in relation, not in isolation ‚ô•Ô∏è
sending love to all those working to heal from things they don‚Äôt discuss. and sending strength to start discussing them.
thank you @the_numinous for capturing the thought.

text:
with all that is happening in the world in the past year...with events such as the #metoo movement, dr. ford's testimony against brett kavanaugh, and taylor's very public trial against david mueller... i wanted to make today's post not about a specific woman, but... to the women who have come forward about their sexual assault. to the women who have come forward about their experiences with sexual harassment. to the women who have faced the person who has assaulted them in court. to the women who haven't come forward because they are scared of what people will say. to the women who feel like they have to suffer in silence. to the women who may not have experienced these particular events but are supporting and helping in any way they can women who have. to the women who keep fighting every day for their rights. to the women giving a voice to women everywhere. 
from the bottom of my heart, thank you. we all need to do our part to make the world a better place. anyone reading this...please share in the comments what organizations you like supporting when it comes to these issues. i would love to help in any way i can. ‚ù§
.
.

text:
listen up!! recently i was with a group of strong, confident, outspoken women and something happened i cannot shake. we were a group celebrating our friends bachelorette party and we asked our uber driver to take a picture of us with our phone. afterwards he immediately pulled his out and said ‚Äúwait now let me get one on mine.‚Äù no thanks! right? well, despite how all of us felt and the comments we said under our breath we stood there and allowed him to take a picture of us on his own phone. 
any of us girls could have said ‚Äúno‚Äù, walked away and would have allowed the others to follow. these are some of the strongest and fierce ladies i know but something we have all been taught is to be polite, don‚Äôt make him feel uncomfortable and essentially just keep your mouth shut despite how you feel.

it would have been so easy just to say ‚Äúno‚Äù and walk away. non of us even challenged him but all of us were uncomfortable and didn‚Äôt want him to take our photo for him to keep. 
this is so maddening to me and i share this to say that we must speak up ladies. 
be the ‚Äúbitch‚Äù you‚Äôre scared of being. don‚Äôt allow a man or anyone else intimidate you. do not diminish yourself because you‚Äôre afraid someone else will be uncomfortable!
and to the men in our lives encourage your wife, sister, friend to speak up and when they do listen!

text:
why wouldn't a woman want to share her story? shame, perhaps? maybe it's not that she doesn't think you will believe her, maybe she doesn't believe it herself. maybe she doesnt think it 'counts'. that's how i feel. 
as a 30 year old grown adult, when i think about a certain incident that happened, 11 years ago, i find i have a little voice that still says, "yeah but, it doesn't really count." i have no idea why. maybe because at first i was going along with things, and then i remember i changed my mind. it was going to far, i didnt want to anymore. i went into the bathroom, shut the door and sat on the toilet. i looked down and noticed i was bleeding. i started to cry and panic. one of the guys came into the bathroom, without knocking. holding a video camera. i remember telling him no more, go away, i'm done, stop. i'm pretty sure i was kind of laughing when i said it because i was scared, i didnt feel strong enough to be firm, i didnt want to be uncool? he forced himself on me anyway. then he drove me home and i got in the shower and cried and cried and pulled a bloody condom out from deep inside. a part of me died in that moment. that was rape. i knew it then, i know it now, and yet my mind still says "yeah but, maybe it doesnt count." i told my brother about the incident a few years later and he asked me if i reported it/them. i remember saying things like "i couldn't do that, they were my friends, it's not that big a deal, it doesnt really count...etc" and yet, i've thought about this incident tons of times since it happened. it pops up into my mind randomly, i used to have full on panic attacks that the video would one day surface and embarrass me, i've had flashbacks in the middle of healthy sexual intimacy. it scarred me. and i guarantee those 3 guys have never thought about it since. that makes me the most angry. an incident that has haunted me for 11 years they have probably never thought about again. i have felt damaged, ugly, trashy, worthless, stupid, ashamed. ive blamed myself plenty and made excuses. share your stories if you want to, women. 
i believe you. ‚ù§ 
men, hold your brothers accountable. #believewomen #nomeansno #yourstorycounts #metoo

text:
in a time where consent, harassment and assault are at the forefront of society's conversations, its unsettling that porn is championed as empowering when it sexualizes themes such as rape and assault. 
real drugged and passed out
 forced sex videos
unconscious girl 
drugged and used
one simple google search reveals these categories as the top rape porn videos, available and accessible right now.

in other words, the same actions that bill cosby, brett kavanaugh, harvey weinstein and others have been accused of are marketed as sexual fantasy and entertainment¬†to anyone with an internet signal and a device with a screen. the same degrading "locker room" rhetoric we rightfully pushback against is also used in pornographic scripts.  how is this acceptable?

how is it that our culture rightly speaks out against rape and abuse, yet there isn‚Äôt also outcry for the porn that depicts the same and far worse?

if we‚Äôre really going to tackle the issue of sexual abuse as a society, we need to be aware of all the places where this harmful behavior is normalized, and even promoted.

to anyone effected by the #metoo movement or the surge of publicity surrounding sexual assault in our society, i stand with you, and i will continue to fight for your right to be safe.

text:
it‚Äôs about honoring the wisdom in the feminine. it‚Äôs about the balance of masculine and feminine. what created the problem in the first place is the toxic masculinity. ego and logic driven. the problems in the world cannot be solved with the same thought that created them. we must approach these problems from another perspective. rather than saturating yourself with the information, you need to deeply feel the collective pain of the planet. fememnine values need to be brought in. deep feeling and listening, being with thechaos and unknown. and most improtantly bringing yourself back to your heart every moment. every time you find yourself going back into fear stop taking in negativity, and process what you already know. let yourself feel, cry, yell, rage, grieve the reality that we have created together because we have so forsaken our hearts. we have let the mind, ego, and intellect drive everything to create so much damage, cause so much pain in the collective. so the best thing to do right now is look within. look at the places you forsake in yourself. all the places you don‚Äôt want to feel. and be honest with yourself about it all. anywhere that you do not fully love and accept yourself is a place where the collective can‚Äôt move forward until it‚Äôs healed. we all co create this reality and when i say we need to shift from fear into love i mean this process. all the places where you fear and judge yourself. heal those. and once your heart and body is vibrating at the frequency of pure unconditional love, i promise we will see a change on the planet.
