text:
venus went retrograde on october 5th until november 16th. this retrograde is a particularly forceful one happening in the intense and powerful sign of scorpio with venus in an active square with mars who‚Äôs conjunct black moon lilith (bml) in aquarius. it is easy to explain this transit by turning on the news. women are furious with cold hearted men and they are standing up to make it known. this is happening to break the spell that was cast to enslave women so many centuries ago.

let‚Äôs explain this a bit deeper. venus is the planet that represents our inner feminine, goddess, mother, wife, sister, daughter, etc. where she was located at the time of your birth is what sort of woman energy you embody and how you like to be honored as a woman. also where she is located in present time is what sort of energy she is beaming to earth to arouse our birth venuses. 
right now she is beaming scorpio retrograde which is the very dangerous woman who loves and hates the dark. the perfect archetype for her is the ancient sumerian goddess lilith who is one bad ass who has been villainized throughout almost every century and religion. many of her stories are wicked ‚Äì murmurs of stealing and eating babies and happily cavorting with demons.  they have called her the bride of the devil and the patriarchy has seemed determined to make lilith an object of fear and loathing because she is a woman who disobeys, flees from and rages at men. she scares.them.to.death. but in truth, lilith is a banner for female power, authenticity, sexuality and the act of reclaiming parts of our selves that are vital for survival. 
with bml conjunct mars in aquarius squaring scorpio retrograde venus, there is something dangerous in the air. something dangerous but also game changing. you might find ancient skeletons that you had carefully tucked away in locked chests rattling out in the open to be addressed and laid to rest. many women‚Äôs ‚Äúme too‚Äù stories are being made public for the first time and men are finding themselves needing to examine their preconceived attitudes of the women in their lives. 
this is really very needed.....finally  #venusretrograde #shamanicastrology #metoo #lilith

text:
saw "the kiss" by francesco hayez this morning.
little did i know that a few hours later a 64 year old architect from lake como named marco (or so he said) would offer to buy me a drink (i don't drink) and proceed to grab me and shove his tongue down my throat.  and do it again after i pushed him away.  and a third time.  there may have been a fourth, it was hard to keep track what with focusing all of my attention on getting his mouth and hands off of me.
i swear, some guys are seriously learning impaired. 
if i had to be kissed by some rando in italy, couldn't it have been the tunisian businessman living in japan but on a work trip to turin (or so he said) who tried to pick me up (very politely i might add) at the cafe in the egyptian museum??? at least he wasn't old enough to be my father.  geez.

and yes, i finally got away from the dirty old man. 
#thekiss #francescohayez #brera #italy #milan #travelphoto #museumphoto #nomeansno #metoo

text:
i struggle with anxiety. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
the word is thrown around way too much and way too casually. for those of us that have suffered from anxiety we know that it can quite literally derail you from everyday normalcy. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
when i was in my last semester in college, i decided to take my capstone within a graduate level course on shakespearean sonnets. my concentration of study had been mostly within renaissance literature, so i thought i was prepared. what i wasn't prepared for is that only 6 other, very smart people going for their doctorates also were taking the class, so their was a lot of participation required. i hate speaking in front pretty much anyone that i feel is going to be judging me. the fear of public speaking... apply that to one on ones, first dates, small groups, large groups... pretty much anything that doesn't include my closest friends and family. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
while taking my capstone, i was taking a few other classes, classical theater, another shakespeare course, a basic statistics course (for the third time... can't i just pass it already), working 30 hours a week at two different jobs, maintaining my social life, and i just started to work on my certification to teach yoga. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
and that was it, i was in the middle of a yin yoga class and bam.. i couldn't breath. it felt as if the whole world decided to turn in and consume me. my heart beat so fast. after 5 minutes but what felt like hours, i finally able to go home. but the next week it happened again. i was on my way to church to speak with my pastor about being re-baptized.. looking back, it was probably something i was trying to force something too soon. after a visit to my doctor, i was put on anxiety medicine and was told to slow down. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
honestly, i felt like a failure. but now i see it as god's way of telling me to narrow my focus. perfect one task at a time rather than overwhelming yourself by trying to perfect them all. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
if you've made it this far... wow, thank you so much letting me share a little bit of my past and heart with you. i'd love to chat with you more about this because apparently there is a limit on ig caption characters. send me a message or drop a comment, and i'll message you. ‚ù§

text:
‚ú® i‚Äôve made myself smaller, shrunk my body to make space for you. but i need space too. i need space to move.
i‚Äôve made myself quiet, silenced every thought that wasn‚Äôt soft.  but i have anger, i have anger too. ‚ú®

every time i listen to @lindsaykaymusic song ‚Äútoo‚Äù i tear up a little (or a lot). there are so many times in my life when i‚Äôve forced myself into modes of being that weren‚Äôt me, i‚Äôve made myself small, i‚Äôve pushed down my rage, and still made sure to smile, to dress nice, to change myself first. i need a break from thinking of myself as a woman, i need a break from remembering all the times someone assumed ownership of my body. i wish i was surprised that dr. fords testimony didn‚Äôt matter. but i‚Äôm not surprised. i‚Äôve always known that it wouldn‚Äôt matter. one day we were all sitting on hard chairs in a dark room watching a documentary in school. the boy sitting next to me and next to his girlfriend on the other side slipped his hand under my sweater and into my skirt and i didn‚Äôt say anything. because i knew it didn‚Äôt matter, and i knew that to him it was my fault. that same year i had a ‚Äúboyfriend‚Äù whom i didn‚Äôt like, who i never said yes to, who was 17 and took my virginity. i didn‚Äôt know how to say no, and i felt like i couldn‚Äôt. our ‚Äúrelationship‚Äù ended because a group of older boys spread a rumor that i hooked up with one of their friends on a field trip. actually, we were all in a hot tub and he touched me and i didn‚Äôt know how to say no to that either. this was right before spring break. i went home and got the chicken pox and my aim was full of hateful messages about how i was a whore. i was 13. i already knew that the truth didn‚Äôt matter. i already knew that my body was a weapon, and not one i could yield. assault doesn‚Äôt have to be loud, it doesn‚Äôt have to be violent. if any of them happened to read this, i don‚Äôt think they would remember. but i remember, and i have a long list, leading all the way up to october 2017. i don‚Äôt want to wear this like a badge, i don‚Äôt want to yell #metoo . i lost my voice on saturday and i‚Äôm just getting it back today...and that seems very fitting. let‚Äôs all channel our anger and register to vote todayüí•

text:
‚ú® listen up! ‚ú®

i‚Äôm switching gears for a second to talk about something else i‚Äôm super passionate about‚Äî

1 in 3 girls and 1 in 6 boys are sexually abused.  100% of women are sexually harrassed. as a therapist, i hear these stories all the time. as a mom of 3 girls, it‚Äôs a conversation i make sure to have casually but frequently. 
i was having one of these conversations with paisley today while we were making a smoothie and i felt like i needed to use this little platform of mine to share. 
friends and therapy clients constantly ask me how to talk to our kids about heavy topics like these. i never had conversations like this when i was a kid. i encountered surprise situations, as i‚Äôm sure all of you have too, where i didn‚Äôt really know what to say and didn‚Äôt know if i could have a voice. i hope my daughters will always know they have a voice and they can use it. 
watch my stories to see my un-rehearsed, candid conversation with her. this is one of hundreds of conversations we have and will have about this topic throughout her life. girls aged 3 and 4 are the most at risk. so start talking to them when they‚Äôre young!

please share this with your mom friends.

#honestmotherhood #parenting #motherhood #motherhoodunplugged #motherhoodthroughinstagram #momlife #ldsmom #ldsblogger #protectingchildren #keepthemsafe #consent #metoo #metoomovement

text:
‚Äúwives, submit yourselves to your husbands as you do to the lord...husbands, love your wives as christ loved the church and gave his life for it.‚Äù ephesians 5:22-25.
.
.
i see this verse quoted a lot in relation to the #sexualassualt cases that are so public in our media right now. i see it as a way of stating that religion, or christianity, encourages a woman to be beneath her husband. and it saddens my heart, because people so often leave off the second part of this #scripture that calls men to love and give their lives for their wives.
.
.
my husband and i had this verse read at our wedding, and i intentionally left the word ‚Äúsubmit‚Äù in the translation. why?.
.
.
i love my husband. i trust my husband, and i trust his judgement. i trust that when my husband hears from the lord and feels a calling on his life from him, that he will lead our family in the right direction. and i gladly submit to my husband‚Äôs guidance in areas of our marriage.
.
.
in the same respect, my husband loves me and values my thoughts and opinions. if he is ever making a choice that my gut tells me is wrong, harmful, or misguided, i know my husband‚Äôs #love for me allows him to value my thoughts and advice.
.
.
choosing to #submit to your husband, as scripture says, does not make you less than. it does not mean your husband is ‚Äúbetter‚Äù than you or above you in your marriage, and too often we forget the calling on our husbands to love us enough to die for us..
.
.
.#church #christian #faith #love #trust #ephesians #metoo #marriage #christslove

text:
profiles in courage: johanna tropiano
_____________
human rights has always been a passion of johanna‚Äôs, from working with an orphanage in nicaragua to serving on the board of a rape crisis and domestic violence shelter. since 2007, johanna has been heavily involved in issues of justice, and in 2011 she joined the international justice mission to work on human trafficking and abuse issues. being a survivor of child sexual assault and working through the shame from that and finding healing was what gave her the passion that fuels her advocacy. she is now writing a book about my experiences and also transitioning into working with incarcerated women. ‚Äúwithin the church, there is sadly still so much denial as the abuse that goes on. to this day, people don‚Äôt want to believe what happened to me or that mine is a typical experience for survivors of abuse.‚Äù when asked to explain, johanna replied that she ‚Äúexperienced additional trauma in the church several times‚Äù when she went to people in my church for help. ‚Äúthey minimized the abuse that was being done to me or blamed me for it. my hope is that the church really begins to wake up and boldly repent for abuse they have done to victims and then begin to implement policies to protect survivors and confront perpetrators rather than shield them.‚Äù when not advocating for others, johanna spends time with her family. she has been married for five years and just celebrated their daughter‚Äôs first birthday. johanna is a museum-buff, and enjoys living in la where there are so many museums and cultural points of reference. 
johanna is an avid reader and is in the middle of ‚Äúthe body keeps the score‚Äù by van der kolk and a young adult book called ‚Äúlord of the opium‚Äù for fun it‚Äôs my favorite pastime. music-wise, she‚Äôs listening to glass animals and gungor. 
perseverance is her chief characteristic. ‚Äúmy idea of perfect happiness is holding my sleeping baby with my husband and a delicious glass of wine next to me. preferably some place exotic or old, like italy or bali. that sounds like perfection.‚Äù _____________
#johannatropiano  #profileincourage #courageconference2018 #metoo #churchtoo

text: almost one year ago #metoo exploded in to the consciousness of the world. it‚Äôs hard for me to imagine a world without me too anymore. it‚Äôs the moment that women broke their silence, and it‚Äôs the moment we took our power back through raising our voices and learning that we can and should be heard. we own that right, we deserve that right. i‚Äôm thankful to the women who have shared their stories, the women i know and i love. these women who are rape survivors, abuse survivors, trafficked survivors, and so much more. i hold each of them here tonight these friends i have who‚Äôve endured so much and i want to say that i hope somehow and i pray, there will never have to be another women who says me too. somehow i hope for that and while we move towards that dream together, i know we are not alone. i salute the brave women who are survivors, you have all changed my life in huge ways. i have learned that i can speak up and i can be brave. i can fight and i can say a lot more than i could before. thank you ‚ù§Ô∏è #survivors #thankyou #empowerwomen #womenstrong #timesup üì∏ by my amazing friend and kickass survivor sarah isaacs ‚ù§Ô∏è#silenceisnotspiritual

a victim of sexual assault is most likely to tell a friend before they tell anyone else. how will you respond?
‚ö†Ô∏è safety tip: support often means listening. you can let your friend know that you believe them, it is not their fault and they are not alone. sometimes support can also mean helping your friend get medical attention, helping your friend report the assault, or reaching out to the national sexual assault hotline 1-800-656-4673. for more information on how to support your friend visit https://www.rainn.org/articles/tips-talking-survivors-sexual-assault

text:
a federal lawsuit filed in california in april 2016 against #jeffreyepstein and #donaldtrump by a california woman alleged the men sexually assaulted her at a series of parties at epstein's manhattan home in 1994, when she was 13 years of age. the suit was dismissed by a federal judge in may 2016 because it didn't raise valid claims under federal #law . the woman filed another federal suit in new york in june 2016, but it was withdrawn 3 months later, apparently without being served on the defendants. a third federal suit was filed in new york in september 2016. the 2 latter suits included affidavits by an anonymous witness who attested to the accusations in the suits, and an anonymous person who declared the plaintiff had told him/her about the assaults at the time they occurred. the plaintiff, who had filed anonymously as¬†jane doe, was scheduled to appear in a los angeles press conference six days before the 2016 election, but abruptly canceled the event; her lawyer¬†lisa bloom asserted the woman had received threats. the suit was dropped on november 4, 2016. trump attorney alan garten flatly denied the allegations, while epstein declined to comment. in january 2015, a 31-year-old american woman, virginia roberts, alleged in a sworn affidavit that at the age of 17 she had been held as a¬†sex slave¬†by epstein. she further alleged that he had¬†trafficked¬†her to several people, including¬†#princeandrew¬†and¬†harvard law¬†professor¬†#alandershowitz . roberts also claimed that epstein and others had physically and sexually abused her. roberts alleged that the #fbi may have been involved in a¬†#coverup . she said she had served as epstein's sex slave from 1999 to 2002 and had recruited other under-age girls. epstein entered an out-of-court settlement. source: wikipedia

text:
i am writing to answer the question " who the hell are you?" i am writing this to say " hoti kaun hay be tu?" i am the rain. i am the slow meaningless invisible vapor that gathers around and creates a powerful nimbus cloud that pours down effortlessly if you want it or not and fertilizes your land, oh men. i am not the conditional purchase that you make with another man. 
but my heart is an open book where i keep the records written on with blood and sweat. you won't be forgotten. i am not a sofa where you can sit firmly upon, pressing your ass or rubbing your boner.

i am that bridge that connects you with your senses. i am a representative of the genius animal race or the better half of it. i am the national anthem you sing with respect and the only time of the day when you keep your spine straight.

you are expressing your firm determination to do or die, i am that determination. i am that precious emerald that you are wearing to change your inevitable luck. i am an old fortress of rajasthan that saw plenty of women dying to save your fragile meaningless honor.

i am a thousand illegitimate war children, that you created by raping weaker people as a projection of your power. i am that unapologetic stomach that can digest you, your body-shaming nature and your ego in a second. i am that mother you have wronged by millennium years of forgery.

if you still ask any woman " who the hell are you or kaun hain be tu?" remember we are the mirror who is detecting your fraud, without any advanced technology, since forever, so be scared. be very very scared. #metoo

i cross the street at night when there is a park or a dark alley. i don‚Äôt leave my drink unattended at a bar and i take them only from friends and bartenders directly. i don‚Äôt leave bars alone. and after two of my friends were pulled into cars, i started looking over my shoulder when walking to my car in the dark. i‚Äôve had a bus driver drop me off in front of my house when i felt uncomfortable. i carry bear spray when i hike alone and i carry my phone in my hand in the city when i feel something isn‚Äôt right. i pay attention to my surroundings and who i am with. i am vigilant no matter what situation i‚Äôm in. i am careful. i have always been careful.
‚Ä¢
but being careful didn‚Äôt stop me from ending up in a bad situation.
‚Ä¢
thanks to the brave voices of some of my friends, i thought it was time to join the conversation. you can read my story about why i‚Äôm happy to be living in a time that is scary for young men on my blog (link in profile).

text:
i read this before i watched the movie, back when the movie came out. i'm so glad i did. what an amazing book. i liked the movie, but i wouldn't have understood half of the things in it without having read this first.
.
this book was the first instance i read of where a parent sold their daughter into slavery because they couldn't afford to feed them. i was shocked. since then, i have read of many similar, true accounts, and it still breaks my heart every time‚Äîwhich is one of the reasons i wrote finding heaven, to help raise awareness of the issue. it still happens around the globe.
.
as far as "memoirs of a geisha," definitely a book i want to re-read at some point.
.
can you think of a fiction book that opened your eyes to a real-world problem you became passionate about addressing?
.

text:
hi everyone! here is a picture of me and my dog, stevie. if you care about us, or yourself, or your dog....or your children...family...future...or opinion then i urge you to vote on november 6th!!! yes this is a political post. but i‚Äôm not looking for debates or arguments, i‚Äôm not looking at red or blue. i‚Äôm looking for everyone to take action. the midterms are often looked over and swept under the rug. we are not educated as much about the midterms so that the elected officials can keep their careers for as long as possible. we are told our vote doesn‚Äôt matter because you are only one person. that is a tactic to get you to not vote. i am here to tell you that there is power in numbers! numbers of women have shifted our culture into a movement. numbers of teenagers have put pressure on elected officials to change or at the very least be concerned about their safety in schools. numbers of people of color have shouted that they matter, and people have listened! there is power in numbers! do not let those in power tell you that your vote doesn‚Äôt matter! if you are tired, fed up, and want better for the future then vote on november 6th! not voting is a way of oppressing yourself and for those in power to keep you silent. even if your pick doesn‚Äôt win at least you can argue with the status quo. it‚Äôs time to shift ‚Äúme too‚Äù into a movement of ‚Äúi too made a difference‚Äù today is the last day to register to vote in many states. check that you are registered and you know where your voting location is. the government has made it systematically difficult for us to vote. show them otherwise!
‚Ä¢
#metoo #blacklivesmatter #marchforourlives #midterms2018 #vote #america #stopoppression

text:
i don‚Äôt normally watch it, but tonight‚Äôs eastenders episode is so so important. 
i‚Äôm not a man hater but for any man that thinks the #metoo is ‚Äútoo harsh on men‚Äù and makes it feel like ‚Äúthey can‚Äôt do anything‚Äù is a joke. it isn‚Äôt hard to ask simple questions to get consent. 
we‚Äôre so used to blaming ourselves (men and women) maybe i was too drunk, maybe i was dressed a bit provocative, maybe i was this and that. no. bullshit. if someone has chosen to wear something that shows a bit of flesh on their best asset they should be able to without the threat of rape. if someone‚Äôs flirty it‚Äôs not an invitation for sex it‚Äôs just simple harmless flirting. we should be able to drink, wear what we want, behave how we want without the threat of rape. 
i know there‚Äôs disgusting people out there that lie about abuse and rape and they should be ashamed of themselves. it makes victims not want to come forward because they don‚Äôt want to be branded a liar as so many have lied. 
anyone that says someone deserves to be raped because of what they wore or because of their drunken state well you should be ashamed. people need to be supported not told it was their fault because i‚Äôm sure they probably already feel it was their fault, which of course it is not. it‚Äôs never the victims fault.

text:
gratitude day #21
üôèüèº
grateful for finding my voice. for expression and creativity. .
been hesitating to share this post but it's time to stop procrastinating üôåüèº. i realized it was shame and the thought "what will people think of me". .
time to move forward. .
.
i grew up learning that children are to be seen but not heard. .
i would hear ‚Äúshhh, nothing happened‚Äù, ‚Äúit‚Äôs ok, you‚Äôre fine‚Äù. in different places, from different people. .
and this is the inner dialogue i carried through much of my life.  and no blame on anyone or anything - because that‚Äôs simply what those people who said those words also learnt in their lives.  it‚Äôs generational. it‚Äôs in our genes.  it‚Äôs culture and society. .
when i had unusual symptoms in 2005 after the birth of my son - such as fatigue, headaches, tingling in my hand/foot (with no diagnosis found at the time) - i kept silent. in my head i thought, "the doctors didn't find anything, it must just be me. and maybe this us part of becoming a mother. in hindsight it was unresolved trauma and the related (unprocessed) emotions. maybe some would've called it (post-partum) anxiety/depression.
when i had bells palsy in 2009, i took time off work and literally hid in my home for 3 weeks until some facial movement returned. .
when "trauma stuff" surfaced in 2014, i remained silent. 
when i was experiencing ‚Äúacute stress disorder‚Äù and ‚Äúadrenal fatigue‚Äù in 2015 i plodded along in silence. .
but more and more my body would no longer allow for silence.  emotions wanted to be felt and expressed. .
finally this years concussion spoke to me and said ‚Äúit‚Äôs time to speak up, it‚Äôs time to speak up for yourself‚Äù. i trust it is unfolding as it is meant to, even though i'm not always clear on its meaning. .
i feel i am being called to share this journey because so many are in a similar place - yet feel alone or ashamed of being sick, unemployed, out of a relationship, different from the norm and society - or anything that makes you feel small, that you are less than whole, that you are not enough). .
we teach what we learn. 
it's why i do the work i do. .
shame takes away your light. 
remember. ‚ú®you are whole. you are enough

text:
sexual trauma survivor. 
generational trauma survivor. 
white christian supremacy survivor. 
police brutality survivor. 
ethnographic researcher (impact of mass incarceration on the life trajectories of black women and girls) 
trauma counseling clinician. 
crisis counselor for the wake forest university safe office (i support students that experience sexual trauma & intimate partner violence) 
wake forest university school of divinity 2nd year student. 
i‚Äôve consciously made the decision that after this second masters is done (2020) i‚Äôm not pursuing a doctoral degree. surviving mostly white spaces is exhausting and my life has been a grueling fight for survival. 
at this point, i‚Äôm only interested in holistic, sustainable, and transformative healing that supports individual & communal capacity building. womanist praxis is a way of life. i wish i knew 10 yrs ago that i was doing more than just surviving. 
i have the tools needed to do the work that my soul requires me to do. i‚Äôm not about to kill myself trying to obtain any more titles to prove that i‚Äôm worthy. 
i‚Äôm starting to write. it would be such a disservice to not share how i‚Äôve been able to survive and make it through so many intersecting systems of oppression. #metoo #survivor #blackwomenaremagic #graduatestudent #makingmoves #gratitude

text:
something that really helped me "get by" when i was still struggling with ptsd?

naps!

anyone else a huge fan of naps?! when i couldn't sleep through the night, naps were my savior.. 15 minutes here and there throughout the day kept me functioning just enough

i personally still love napping and i take 1 short nap (about 20 minutes) everyday

according to the national sleep foundation naps also have a lot of benefits like: - providing an easy way to get relaxation and  rejuvenation
- restoring alertness
- enhancing performance
- reducing mistakes 
so if you're anything like i was and you're having trouble sleeping through the night.. naps might bring you some much needed relief! (brad & shiloh love naps too) üòäüí§üê∂

text:
yesterday was a hard day to witness for at least a million women. for women who have felt silenced and those who are empathetic to that silence. my colleague at work brought up the kavo case and i was so inedited with my to do list that i told her i couldn‚Äôt even watch the news anymore or talk about it because it was so upsetting and i don‚Äôt have time to get brought by it again. i allowed her to talk about her fears regarding the outcome and how the courts will now be run but only briefly before we got back to business. 
this morning i woke up with a even heavier heart because i realized that yesterday was a perfect example of the how and why of this current reality and more insight into the reasons these things continue to happen. it‚Äôs because as women we are 16x more powerful than men but that power comes from our sensitivity and intuition. the forgo our power by suppressing or numbing our feelings. i (and many others) allow the day to day wear me down so much that i don‚Äôt have the energy to stand up for what is right. i use so much emotional strength bottling my feelings in that when something happens i am so hurt i cannot fight. ladies, that is the current societies plan. we are bred to compete with one another for unattainable perfection so we are too ‚Äúbusy‚Äù to see the bigger picture of what is happening around us. we don‚Äôt believe others because we are told that other women are a threat and that we can only trust our inner circle and our men. 
yesterday it was clear that women were given the message that even when they use their voices, it doesn‚Äôt matter. but i don‚Äôt believe that can continue on. it‚Äôs the dawn of a new age and the women to come are raised in a new and improved frequency. and i will not stay stuck in the times in the past. i am ready to use that 16x of my power to speak up for what is right. * (continued in next comment)*

yesterday it was clear that women were given the message that even when they use their voices, it doesn‚Äôt matter. but i don‚Äôt believe that can continue on. it‚Äôs the dawn of a new age and the women to come are raised in a new and improved frequency. and i will not stay stuck in the times in the past. i am ready to use that 16x of my power to speak up for what is right. * (continued in next comment)*

text:
"she stands and embraces me, more to give herself comfort than to impart it, and her hands describe small circles all over my back. i do not melt into it -- the memory of the original pain, and the night i snuck into my parents' room to tell them, and their reaction, is still too vivid. it prickles over the skin like a sweat, or a flush. my mind fixes on the indelible image of kneeling next to my mother's side of the bed, in that bedroom filled with decorative gold balls, and telling her what had happened, and her asking with a sob, "but you didn't sleep with him beforehand, did you?" and when i told her i had, of my father rising, holding me against his great patriarchal stomach, and making the sign of the cross over me to absolve me of my sins. it moves next to the image of sitting in the cold, clinical office of the pro-life gynecologist my mother had designated for all her daughters, and telling him what had happened and hearing him say, "well, now you've learned that you can't trust everyone, can you," in a voice wiped entirely of human sympathy, as he squared my file with two brisk taps against his desk and stood to leave. it must have been then that i began to suspect, something is not right with the way these people have arranged the world, no matter what their intentions."
.
i was going to make a post about how thankful i am for the laughs provided by priestdaddy, and then i hit this doozy of a passage, which mirrors the experience of so many women and girls, and is punching me in the gut over and over again. and that's the beauty of this book -- you're laughing out loud for 100 pages, and then suddenly you're crying. while i find it unfocused and hard to keep track of at times, when it hits, man does it hit.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
my grandparents graciously let me interview them last christmas and it turned into the most meaningful film i‚Äôve made. 
growing up, i always saw how much my family respected and treasured my grandparents, but it wasn‚Äôt until my adult years that i could truly appreciate how special they really are. i come from a large family and they made each of us feel intimately cared for. this film was one that i felt responsible for making because i believe we need more stories about people who truly love others well. 
you‚Äôll notice this film is called 'the patriarch' and covers my grandfather‚Äôs life, but i hope that you‚Äôll also notice that it is equally about my grandmother and how vital she is to the cleary family. i‚Äôve been hesitant to share the name of the film because i‚Äôm very sensitive to the #metoo movement, #ibelieveher and general feelings of old white men in positions of authority. it is not my intention to argue for or to support ‚Äúpatriarchy‚Äù, simply to provide an example of a man and woman who provided their family with an exceptional example of leadership. 
i had the opportunity to screen this film for my family this past weekend at their 60th wedding anniversary and it was incredible. my grandparents have touched so many lives and it was evident that a life lived in sacrifice to others is the most rewarding. i hope you‚Äôll watch and enjoy the film. link in bio.

text:
i want to shed some light on things after hearing the debates of the #kavanaugh situation. let me start by making it clear that i am not an investigator and not trying to say anyone did or didn‚Äôt do anything. 
i do want to say that victims question themselves on whether it happened or it didn‚Äôt, if the violation was somehow their responsibility (i was drunk, i chose to stay, etc), and this makes it hard for them to come forward when it happened. it‚Äôs not that they can‚Äôt remember clearly what happened. they do. they sometimes choose to suppress to survive since society has taught them to carry the blame and they won‚Äôt be believed. it‚Äôs not unusual for others to come out with their experiences when hearing others similar experiences. this happens in a group therapy process, this happens amongst conversation with friends. it is very brave for someone carrying so much guilt and shame towards themselves to admit something wrong was done to them. it‚Äôs not okay that many of us would choose to protect our sons and basically say it‚Äôs okay to rape, but teach our daughters that they are responsible for getting themselves raped.

text:
in the city of clarkston where i live, we have a developer that is trying to come in and bring in too much religion, in my opinion. we are a diverse mix of people, races and religion. why do we try to convert other people to our way of believing? that is another way of expressing tokenism. the person is only able to be in our space if they look like us and behave like us. not healthy.  this image is in so many of our front yards in clarkston and i love it. a home with a heart in it is a place you know that you are loved and accepted. it shows a place where you are not a token. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚Äúhave you ever thought of counting the toll it takes on the person who is made a token? i had an experience recently where i became aware of the fact that a person i was in relationship with might be unaware that i experience it as tokenism. it was painful, but i share it with you so that you may consider the damage this ultimately does to the human soul.‚ÄùÔøΩ‚†Ä
